      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1442">
               <p>Molther was born in <placeName>Alsace</placeName>, educated at Jena, and in <date
                     when="1737">1737</date> became tutor to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2310.xml"/>Count Zinzendorf</persName>&apos;s son
                     <persName>Renatus</persName>. In <date when="1739">1739</date> he was ordained
                  and appointed to missionary work in <placeName>Pennsylvania</placeName>. On <date
                     when="1739-09-05">Sept. 5, 1739</date> he married Countess <persName>Johanna
                     Sophia Seidewitz,</persName> who was designated to follow him to
                     <placeName>Pennsylvania</placeName>. Arriving in <placeName>London</placeName>
                  on <date when="1739-10-18">Oct. 18, 1739</date>, Molther was faced with a three
                  months&apos; delay before his vessel sailed. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1113.xml"/>James Hutton</persName> introduced him to
                  the Fetter Lane Society, where he was distressed with the popular charismatic
                  phenomena, which seemed a form of compensation for spiritual hunger. In reaction
                  he encouraged a type of quietism, nearing complete separation from all
                  church-related activities. This led to the disruption of the society on <date
                     when="1740-07-20">July 20, 1740</date>, and drew <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> into correspondence with
                  Molther. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 780–81.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
